{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
The '''Institute for Research in Information and Scholarship (IRIS)''' was founded at [[Brown University]] by [[Andries van Dam]], William S. Shipp, and [[Norman Meyrowitz]] in 1983 and closed in 1991. It was initially part of a campus-wide effort at Brown to develop a "scholar's workstation."

The [[Intermedia (hypertext)|Intermedia]] advanced [[hypertext]] authoring system was the most significant project developed at IRIS.

IRIS partnered with the [[Getty Research Institute|Getty Art History Information Program]] to conduct a study of the research methods of art historians in the mid 1980s.  The results of this study can be found in Bakewell, E.; Beeman, W; Reese, C and Schmitt, M., (Gen. Ed.). (1988). Object, image, inquiry: The art historian at work. Santa Monica: CA: Getty Art History Information Program.

