{{Infobox organization | name = The College Club of Boston | image = CC-front.jpg | image_border = | size = 180 | alt = | caption = The College Club of Boston | map = | msize = | malt = | mcaption = | abbreviation = CCB | motto = | formation = {{Start date|1890|12}} | extinction = | type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] | status = Foundation | purpose = Educational | headquarters = | location = [[Boston, Massachusetts]] | coords = {{coord|42.3527259|-71.073338|region:US-MS_type:edu|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | region_served = Boston, [[Boston Public Schools]] | membership = Private | language = English | leader_title = General Manager | leader_name = Edith Toth | main_organ = Board of directors | affiliations = | num_staff = 8 | num_volunteers = 13 | budget = | website = {{URL|thecollegeclubofboston.com}} | remarks = }}
'''The College Club of Boston''' is a private membership organization founded in 1890 as the first [[Women's club|women's college club]] in the United States. Located in the historic [[Back Bay]] of [[Boston, Massachusetts]] at 44 Commonwealth Avenue, the College Club was established by nineteen college educated women whose mission was to form a [[Club (organization)#Social activities club|social club]] where they and other like-minded women could meet and share companionship. The College Club of Boston the oldest residential college club in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=Topical Women |author=Kathleen Burge |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/59149506.html?dids=59149506:59149506&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+26%2C+1991&author=&pub=Boston+Globe+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Topical+women&pqatl=google |url-access=subscription |newspaper=[[Boston Globe]] |page=14 |department=Editorial |date=February 26, 1991 |access-date=February 18, 2011}}</ref>
==History== In December 1890, 76 Marlborough Street, also located in Boston's [[Back Bay]], became the first home of The College Club.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = | first1 = | year = 1890 | title = The Alpha Phi annual .| journal = The journal of the Association of Collegiate Alumnae | volume = 3-5 | pages = 79 | location = | publisher = [[Alpha Phi]] | accessdate = February 19, 2011 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=EdATAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA79&dq=%2276+Marlborough+Street%22#v=onepage&q=%2276%20Marlborough%20Street%22&f=false}}</ref> The building at 76 Marlborough was purchased by Club member Mabel Cummings in 1893.
In April 1905, the College Club acquired the clubhouse at 40 Commonwealth Avenue, which contained an Old English drawing room, a fine big cafe with a male chef, and seven bedrooms, each of which "were furnished and decorated in the colors of various women's colleges: crimson rambler wallpaper for [[Radcliffe College|Radcliffe]], blue silk curtains for [[Wellesley College|Wellesley]], white (with brass beds) for [[Smith College|Smith]], dawn pink and gray for [[Vassar College|Vassar]]."<ref name="Updating">{{cite news |title=Updating The College Club The Leisured Anna Alumna' of Yesteryear Has Given Way To Young Professionals |author=Margo Miller |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/663564201.html?dids=663564201:663564201&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+15%2C+1983&author=Margo+Miller+Globe+Staff&pub=Boston+Globe+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=UPDATING+THE+COLLEGE+CLUB%3B+THE+LEISURED+ANNA+ALUMNA'+OF+YESTERYEAR+HAS+GIVEN+WAY+TO+YOUNG+PROFESSIONALS&pqatl=google |url-access=subscription |newspaper=[[Boston Globe]] |page= |department=Living |date=January 15, 1983 |access-date=February 18, 2011}}</ref> At that time, the College Club served 600 members, which grew to 1,243 members by 1915.<ref name="Updating"/>
In 1924 the Club purchased 44 Commonwealth Avenue, which was the family home of [[Royal E. Robbins School|Royal E. Robbins]], a major stockholder in the [[Waltham Watch Company]], and once the home of American [[Stage (theatre)|stage]] actress [[Maude Adams]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = | first1 = | year = 1956| title = Shop Talk| journal = [[Publishers Weekly]] | volume = 169 | pages = | location = | publisher = [[Frederick Leypoldt]] | accessdate = February 19, 2011 | url = http://www.google.com/search?q=At+that+time%2C+Maude+Adams+and+Miss+Robbins+lived+at+44+Commonwealth+Avenue%2C+directly+behind+the+bookshop+and+now+the+Boston+headquarters+of+the+English-Speaking+Union%2C&btnG=Search+Books&tbm=bks&tbo=1}}</ref> The [[brownstone]] townhouse was built in 1864 and was designed in the [[Victorian architecture#North America|High Victorian style]].
From its earliest days, The College Club was host to literary luminaries such as [[Mark Twain]], [[Vladimir Nabokov]], poet [[Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr.|Oliver Wendell Holmes]], and novelist [[F. Marion Crawford]]. Other well-known visitors to the Club have included actress [[Sarah Bernhardt]], social activist [[Julia Ward Howe]], abolitionist and suffragist [[Lucy Stone]], health care advocate [[Judy Norsigian]] and Senator [[Edward M. Kennedy]].
Club members took up the cause of [[Philanthropy#Philanthropy.27s Contributions to American Life|educational philanthropy]] in 1985 and established The College Club Scholarship Fund, Inc. as an [[501(c)#501.28c.29.283.29|IRS 501(c)(3)]] designated [[Charitable organization#United States|charitable organization]]. The [[Financial endowment#Endowed scholarship/fellowship|endowed fund]] is administered by Club members. Each year since 1986, the Scholarship Fund has awarded [[college tuition]] assistance to deserving high school seniors from [[Boston Public Schools]].
On May 20, 2002, the City of Boston certified the club's status as the oldest (i.e., first) women's college club in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}
